target_title: Typing coordinates doesn't work

note.body:
Yeah, the issue here is that currently we immediately try to match as soon as the entered string can be parsed as a coordinate (geo: or raw numeric decimal coords, and so on). I think in some cases this gets "tangled up" with autocompletion.

As a work-around it should be possible to copy-paste the string into the search bar.

I think one possible way to make this work better could be something like:

* If pasting in a string, check if it matches the "coord regex", if so, immediatly go that place, otherwise just "inject" the string as if it was a regular search term
* During normal "search-as-you-type", if the entered string matches the "coord regex", insert "fixed" "placeholder place" in the list (and then let the user just select that in the same way as any "regular" search match). And if the search string didn't return any normal search result, but matches a coordinate expression, just show that as a sole search result. These search results could be shown with either "compass" icon used for the current location, or maybe use the "needle" icon that is available from the GNOME icon catalog (distinguished from the generic place marker icon).

note.body: Thank you for explaining! I laid out my issues with dark maps in [#691 (comment)](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-maps/-/issues/691#note_2302196). In short, please consider age and individual vision impairment when making color decisions.

target_title: Add dark style preference

note.body:
We have to distinguish between the dark-mode of the app and that of the content. I believe the content of the map is too specific to the preference of the user to not be configurable.

I'm at an age that **requires me to wear glasses**, and my sight worsens every year. In the car I use light-mode for the maps at all times. My eyes have a **hard time adapting** from light- to dark-mode every time I enter or leave a tunnel. Also, when driving at night I find it very hard to understand the map in dark-mode, my eyes need more light to quickly orient themselves. :eyes: 

The same goes for GNOME Maps when I use them. I use and prefer dark-mode in GNOME everywhere, also in GitLab for example, but a dark map in GNOME Maps is practically unusable with my eyes, at my age I guess. It feels so wrong, **like a negative** that you need a backlight projector for. I had to got back to Google Maps for my map needs, a horrible fallback. Only today I figured out that I can switch the global GNOME settings to light-mode temporarily when I want to use GNOME Maps—though the light application frame then hurts my eyes. :dark_sunglasses: 

So, I do think the [UI style recommendations quoted above](#note_2095807) do apply, some users have special needs for contrast or brightness, especially in applications that have large areas that require the user's attention. It's not just text editing applications, and "long periods of time" is a subjective measurement when your head and your eyes hurt when having to concentrate. :eyeglasses:

Another aspect might be considering tweaking the dark map style a bit.

target_title: Blurry map between some zoom levels

note.body:
This is a bit related to #688 

The issue is that currently the vector renderer renders the tiles at integer zoom levels using cairo into a paintable that is then resized for the intermediate (non-integer) zoom levels.

Ultimatly it should be refactored to use the newer GTK snapshot APIs to draw paths and things like that (that would be rendered "on the fly" on the GPU, or something like that).

That is some work to implement though…
